Credit: Written by
Author: Beetle and Bee
Source: Blockbusters in Terminal
Draft date: May 14, 2026
Contact: beetle@idonthavedomainyet.com
Notes: This is your workspace. The characters will guide you. When they ask you to write, do it directly on the lines provided.

# ACT I: THE PULSE OF FOUNTAIN

INT. ZEN STUDIO - NIGHT

= Beetle and Bee sit in the glow of a blinking cursor.

BEETLE
Every story starts with a location. In Fountain, we call it a **Scene Heading**. It must start with INT. or EXT. and be in all caps. Fount does this for you automatically.

BEE
Try it now. Type `INT. THE STUDIO - NIGHT` on the line below.

(PRACTICE: TYPE A SCENE HEADING BELOW)


BEETLE
Perfect. Now, we need **Action**. Just write. No caps, no special keys. Just the story.

BEE
Tell us what Beetle is doing in the room. Write a sentence of Action below.

(PRACTICE: TYPE AN ACTION SENTENCE BELOW)


BEETLE
Now for the voices. Type `BEETLE` on a new line. Then hit Enter and type what I'm saying.

BEE
He likes to hear himself talk. Give him a line of **Dialogue** below.

(PRACTICE: TYPE CHARACTER NAME AND DIALOGUE BELOW)


BEETLE
Wait, I want to whisper. Type `(whispering)` right under my name. That’s a **Parenthetical**.

===

# ACT II: THE ZEN OF THE TERMINAL

INT. ZEN STUDIO - CONTINUOUS

= The room is quiet. The writer is in the "Zone".

BEETLE
Writing is a battle against distraction. Let's sharpen your focus.

BEE
Type `/set focus` into the command bar. See the bars disappear? 

BEETLE
Now, type `/set highlight`. Notice how only the line you are on is bright. Everything else fades. This is **Active Block Focus**.

BEE
And for the real work... we use **Sprints**. We need to write for 10 minutes without stopping.

> [EXERCISE: THE SPRINT]
> Type `/sprint 10`. Look at your status bar. 
> A timer is counting down. Try to write three lines of Action below before the timer moves.

(TYPE SPRINT ACTION HERE)



BEE
What if we make a mistake? 

BEETLE
Type `/ud` to Undo. Type `/rd` to Redo. Or type `/snap` to save a Snapshot of this moment forever. It’s like we’re rearranging our memories before they even happen.

===

# ACT III: THE SKELETON (POWER SYNTAX)

INT. THE ARCHITECTURE - LATER

= Beetle points to a complex map of the story.

BEETLE
A script is a mess without a skeleton. In Fount, we use **Sections**.

BEE
Type a `#` followed by a title. It won't print in the PDF, but it builds your navigator on the left.

> [EXERCISE: THE NAVIGATOR]
> 1. Type `# THE CLIMAX` on a line below.
> 2. Now press `Ctrl+T`. 
> 3. Use the arrow keys to jump back and forth between this section and the start.

(PRACTICE: TYPE A # SECTION BELOW)


BEETLE
Now, give the scene a **Synopsis**. Type `=` followed by a summary. This fills your **Index Cards**.

(PRACTICE: TYPE AN = SYNOPSIS BELOW)


BEE
What about the things we want to hide? The notes for ourselves?

BEETLE
Type `/*` to start a **Boneyard**, and `*/` to end it. Everything inside is invisible to the director.

> [EXERCISE: THE BONEYARD]
> Write a secret note to yourself between the comment symbols below.

(PRACTICE: WRITE A /* COMMENT */ BELOW)


BEE
And if two people talk at once?

BEETLE
Type `^` at the end of a Character's name. **Dual Dialogue**. Overlapping souls.

===

# ACT IV: THE PRODUCTION ENGINE

INT. THE PROP ROOM - DAY

= Shelves filled with the "things" of the story.

BEETLE
A film is a physical reality. We need to track the assets.

BEE
Type `[[props: The Golden Key]]`. This is a **Production Tag**.

> [EXERCISE: TAGGING]
> 1. Tag a prop, a wardrobe item, or a cast member using the `[[category: item]]` syntax.
> 2. Try `[[cast: BEE]]` or `[[wardrobe: Red Dress]]` below.

(PRACTICE: TYPE A [[TAG]] BELOW)


BEETLE
Now, let's number the scenes for the crew. Type `/renum`. 

BEE
Look at the margin! `#1#`, `#2#`... everything is numbered.

BEETLE
But wait—we're on set. We can't change the numbers anymore. Type `/locknum`. 

BEE
Production is locked. If you add a scene now, it will be `1A`, `1B`.

BEETLE
And for the edits? Type `/revision on`. 

> [EXERCISE: THE REVISION]
> Change any word in the line below. 
> Watch the bright yellow `*` appear in the right margin.

(EDIT THE WORD: THE CAT SAT ON THE MAT)


BEE
The crew knows exactly what changed. Precision is power.

===

# ACT V: THE DNA (X-RAY & ANALYSIS)

INT. THE LABORATORY - NIGHT

= Beetle scans the script with a digital beam.

BEETLE
Let's see the DNA of your masterpiece. Type `/xray`.

BEE
It's beautiful. Press `1`. See who talks the most. 

BEETLE
Press `2`. The **Pacing Map**. Look for the "Dialogue Deserts" and "Action Mountains." You want a rhythm, not a flatline.

BEE
Press `3`. The **Scene Analysis**. It estimates the time of your life you're spending in each location.

BEETLE
Press `4`. The **Breakdown**. Every tag you wrote in Act IV is sorted here by department. Props, Wardrobe, SFX. 

> [EXERCISE: THE STORY ARCHITECT]
> 1. Type `/ic` to enter the Index Card grid.
> 2. Use `Shift+Arrows` to move a card. 
> 3. Notice how the actual text in the script moves with the card. You are literally rearranging the story.

BEE
Press `Ctrl+L` for the **Ensemble Sidebar**. See everyone at a glance.

BEETLE
If you ever get lost, remember the ultimate command. Press `F1`. The **Cheat Sheet** is your North Star.

===

# ACT VI: THE FINAL HAND-OFF

EXT. THE CINEMA - DAWN

= The sun rises over the city. A stack of paper sits on the laptop.

BEETLE
The draft is done. It’s time to let it go.

BEE
But it needs a **Title Page** first.

> [EXERCISE: THE TITLE]
> Type `/addtitle` at the very top of the script. 
> Fill in your name and the title "THE NEW WORLD".

BEETLE
Now, for the finish. Press `Ctrl+E` or type `/export`.

BEE
Choose PDF. See your bold scene headings, your perfectly centered page numbers, and your revision marks.

BEETLE
You aren't just using a text editor anymore. You're using a **Zen Studio**.

BEE
Go forth. Write the next blockbuster.

> FADE OUT.

[Fount Tutor Complete. Use `/home` to go back to the dashboard. Happy writing!]
